						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">SatoshiMatrix wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Based on all this, I think I know where to solder the USB cable wires, but I'm a little unsure. </div> The two grounds is consistent with a mini-B connector â€” they have an extra pin that is tied to +5v, gnd, or left floating to allow for USB OTG support. I don't remember, but assume pin 4 being tied to ground means "this is an endpoint"<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">But I was under the impression that SIXAXIS or Dual Shock 3 controllers needed a special driver.</div> It does, but as far as I can tell, for no reason. The Joystick HID class supports enough axes of analog for all the sticks and all the accelerometers (and even the analog buttons). The only idea that occurs to me is that since all the buttons are (opinion: uselessly) also analog axes, and that's not terribly useful to programs that expect them to be digital.</div>

